Short answer — the API rejects requests and returns rate-limit/error information.

Details from the documentation:
- The API returns HTTP 429 (Too Many Requests) when a monthly query limit is exceeded, with a JSON body containing rate/usage details. Example:
  {
    "success": false,
    "error": "Monthly query limit exceeded",
    "usage": {
      "current": 101,
      "max": 100,
      "exceeded": true,
      "reset_at": "2026-02-01T00:00:00Z"
    }
  }
  - Fields: current (current usage), max (max allowed; -1 = unlimited), exceeded (boolean), reset_at (ISO 8601 time when monthly limit resets).
- Per-minute rate limits also produce 429-style responses. The docs show an example error payload:
  {
    "error": {
      "code": "RATE_LIMIT_EXCEEDED",
      "message": "Rate limit exceeded. Try again in 60 seconds"
    }
  }
- Some query-limit responses may use an INSUFFICIENT_CREDITS error object (example shown in docs).
- Responses include rate-limit headers on every response (e.g. X-RateLimit-Limit, X-RateLimit-Remaining, X-RateLimit-Reset) so clients can monitor remaining quota.

If you want, I can show sample handling/backoff strategies based on the docs (check headers, exponential backoff, cache responses, batch requests).
